# Why Do Republicans Distrust the Media? An In-Depth Analysis

## Introduction

Over the past two decades, trust in traditional media has significantly declined in the United States, with this erosion being particularly pronounced among Republicans. While trust in the media among Democrats has rebounded and even increased in recent years, Republicans' trust has plummeted to historic lows. This report explores the multifaceted reasons behind Republicans' distrust of the media, drawing on extensive polling data, academic research, and expert analyses. It examines the role of perceived media bias, political identity formation, media consumption habits, and the influence of political leadership and partisan media ecosystems. The report also evaluates the implications of this distrust for American democracy and political polarization.

## Historical Trends in Media Trust Among Republicans

Gallup polling data reveal that since at least the late 1990s, Republicans have consistently exhibited lower trust in the media compared to Democrats and independents. However, starting around 2015, this distrust intensified sharply. According to Gallup, trust among Republicans in traditional media outlets fell from 32% in 2015 to just 10% in 2020, while trust among Democrats increased during the same period ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

Similarly, Pew Research Center data show that the percentage of Republicans expressing at least some trust in national news organizations dropped from 70% in 2016 to 35% in 2021, effectively halving in five years. This decline has contributed to the widest partisan gap in media trust recorded since the question was first asked in 2016, with 78% of Democrats expressing trust compared to only 35% of Republicans ([Gottfried & Liedke, 2021](https://www.pewresearch.org/journalism/2021/08/30/partisan-divides-in-media-trust-widen-driven-by-a-decline-among-republicans/)).

| Year | % Republicans Trusting Media | % Democrats Trusting Media | Partisan Gap |
|-------|-----------------------------|----------------------------|--------------|
| 2015  | 32%                         | ~50%+                      | ~18%+        |
| 2016  | 70%                         | 78%                        | 8%           |
| 2020  | 10%                         | Increased                  | ~68%+        |
| 2021  | 35%                         | 78%                        | 43%          |

*Note: Data points are approximate and sourced from Gallup and Pew Research Center.*

## Core Reasons for Republican Distrust in the Media

### 1. Perceived Liberal Bias and Partisan Antagonism

Republicans have long perceived the mainstream media as having a liberal or Democratic Party bias. This perception is reinforced by the increasing association of news media with the Democratic Party, especially amid heightened partisan animosity. For example, a January 2020 YouGov/American Enterprise Institute poll found that 92% of people who voted for then-President Trump agreed that "the mainstream media today is just a part of the Democratic Party" ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

This perception leads Republicans to dismiss news sources that are not aligned with their political views as inherently biased or untrustworthy. The media is often seen not as an impartial institution but as an adversary or extension of the opposing political party.

### 2. Media Consumption Habits and Echo Chambers

Republicans tend to rely heavily on a narrow set of news sources, most notably Fox News, for their political information. Pew Research Center found that among 30 news sources surveyed before the 2020 election, only Fox News was trusted by a majority of Republicans (65%), with the next closest source, ABC News, trusted by only 33% ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

This reliance on a limited range of conservative media outlets, including far-right sources like One America News Network (OAN) and Newsmax, creates an information bubble. Within this bubble, alternative perspectives are often portrayed as "fake news" or part of a liberal conspiracy, further deepening distrust of mainstream media.

The Pew Research Center's 2021 American Values Survey revealed that Republicans who trust far-right media sources hold more extreme views on cultural and political issues compared to those who trust Fox News or other media, illustrating the polarization within Republican media consumption ([Jackson, 2021](https://www.prri.org/research/why-we-divide-republicans-by-media-trust-the-oan-newsmax-effect/)).

### 3. Political Leadership and Rhetoric

The Trump era significantly intensified Republican distrust of the media. Former President Donald Trump openly labeled critical journalists and news organizations as purveyors of "fake news," a term that became a rallying cry among his supporters. This rhetoric not only validated existing suspicions but also politicized media distrust as a core element of Republican identity ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

At Trump campaign events, supporters frequently disparaged and even threatened members of the press, signaling a hostile environment toward media perceived as adversarial. This hostility has persisted, with "fake news" serving as a shibboleth—a symbolic marker—distinguishing Trump-aligned conservatives from other Republicans and the broader public ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

### 4. Media Distrust as Political Identity

Research by political scientists Taeku Lee and Christian Hosam indicates that media distrust among Republicans has evolved from a mere attitude about the institution to a credential of conservatism. Media distrust now functions as a social identity marker, akin to wearing a red MAGA cap, signaling group belonging and ideological alignment ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

Online discourse analysis shows that conservatives use language around "fake news" to create a sense of community ("we" vs. "they") and to establish a shared enemy in the media, reinforcing group cohesion and political identity ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

### 5. Concerns Over Accuracy and Bias

While partisan bias is a significant factor, studies show that Americans, including Republicans, are primarily concerned with accuracy and fairness in news reporting. According to a Gallup/Knight Foundation survey, 89% of Americans say accuracy is very important to their trust in news organizations, and 86% value quick and open correction of mistakes ([Gallup/Knight Foundation, 2018](https://knightfoundation.org/reports/indicators-of-news-media-trust/)).

However, Republicans perceive higher levels of bias, inaccuracy, and misinformation in traditional news media compared to Democrats. They tend to view many major news organizations, except Fox News and The Wall Street Journal, as biased and inaccurate ([Jones, 2018](https://news.gallup.com/poll/237353/americans-misinformation-bias-inaccuracy-news.aspx)).

### 6. Distrust of "Mainstream Media" Label

Republicans who identify their main news source as part of the "mainstream media" report lower trust in that source compared to those who do not label it as such. For example, among Republicans who consider Fox News mainstream, only 32% have a great deal of trust in it, whereas 55% of those who do not consider it mainstream express high trust ([Gottfried, 2021](https://www.pewresearch.org/journalism/2021/07/01/republicans-less-likely-to-trust-their-main-news-source-if-they-see-it-as-mainstream-media/)).

This suggests that the "mainstream media" label itself has become a negative cue among Republicans, further eroding trust.

## The Role of Partisanship and Political Polarization

Partisanship plays a crucial role in shaping media trust. Experimental data from conjoint analyses show that Republicans and Democrats are less likely to trust news organizations perceived as favoring the opposing party, though they do not necessarily trust aligned outlets more than neutral ones ([Gallup/Knight Foundation, 2018](https://knightfoundation.org/reports/indicators-of-news-media-trust/)).

Among Republicans, partisan reputation of a news source is the second most important factor in determining trustworthiness, after how quickly and openly the source corrects mistakes. This underscores how political identity and media trust are intertwined.

## Impact of Media Distrust on Political Opinions and Behavior

Media distrust among Republicans is not just an attitude but influences political opinions and behaviors. Studies indicate that media distrust predicts support for certain policies, such as opposition to pathways to citizenship and affirmative action, and consolidates political tribalism around figures like Trump ([Conroy, 2021](https://fivethirtyeight.com/features/why-being-anti-media-is-now-part-of-the-gop-identity/)).

This distrust also fosters hostility toward news that contradicts their beliefs and excessive trust in preferred outlets, potentially exacerbating misinformation and polarization.

